main event: A star-like object was observed moving slowly in a straight line over Dobbins AFB, Ga., on February 9, 1953. It was believed to be Jupiter at 290° at 5° elevation setting.
interesting points: The object had an orange glow with no visible trail and moved slowly, appearing to stand still for a few minutes.
No sound was heard during the observation.
The visual observation was made by Dobbins Tower operator A/1C J C Williamson.
The object was west of the tower, traveling due west.
Weather conditions at the time of observation included clear visibility up to 12 miles and various wind speeds.
witnesses: Dobbins Tower operator A/1C J C Williamson
